---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/sections/Hero.astro';
import StatBlock from '../../components/sections/StatBlock.astro';
import CTA from '../../components/sections/CTA.astro';
import { pathFor } from '../../i18n/routes';
import { useTranslations } from '../../i18n/utils';

const lang = 'en';
const t = useTranslations(lang);

const stats = [
  { value: '400,000 t', label: 'Sludge generated by Norwegian aquaculture every year (Ragn-Sells)' },
  { value: '~2%', label: 'Share of excrement and feed waste currently collected as sludge (NIBIO)' },
  { value: '66,000 t N / 14,000 t P', label: 'Nitrogen and phosphorus lost to the sea annually (NIBIO)' },
];
---

<BaseLayout lang={lang} pageKey="sustainability" title="Sustainability | FlotLife Nordic" description="Why sludge from Nordic aquaculture and industry is a nutrient resource, not waste — and how collection technology makes recovery possible.">
  <Hero title={t('sustainability.hero.title')} subtitle="Every year, Nordic aquaculture and industry generate sludge rich in nitrogen and phosphorus. Almost none of it is captured. That's not a disposal problem — it's a resource sitting uncollected." />

  <StatBlock stats={stats} heading="The scale of what's being lost" />

  <section class="bg-white">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-10 px-6 py-16 lg:px-8">
      <div>
        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy-950">What's actually in fish sludge</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-neutral-700">
          Fish sludge is a mix of excrement and uneaten feed — in modern land-based salmon
          facilities, uneaten feed can account for as much as half of it (Nofima). Because
          it's essentially unprocessed feed and waste, it carries feed's original nutrient
          load: nitrogen, phosphorus, fats and proteins. Norway's salmon industry uses
          around 2 million tonnes of feed a year to produce 1.5 million tonnes of salmon —
          the gap between those numbers is where sludge comes from.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy-950">Why so little is collected today</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-neutral-700">
          Collection is currently required only at land-based facilities, and even there
          only 30–40% of uneaten feed and feces is captured before it disperses into fine
          particles that escape collection systems (Nofima). At sea-based sites, sludge
          collection has largely been voluntary — but that's changing. SINTEF's OppSlam
          project (2025–2027), backed by FHF and eleven industry and research partners
          including Mowi and Cermaq, is building a calculation model for realistic sludge
          collection potential, driven in part by requirements to protect vulnerable
          seabed habitats near sensitive sites.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy-950">Why phosphorus makes this urgent</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-neutral-700">
          Phosphorus is a finite, geographically concentrated resource — Europe imports most
          of its supply from a small number of countries. Ragn-Sells' AquaPhoenix project,
          backed by €110 million in EU funding, estimates that phosphorus recovery from
          aquaculture sludge could cut Norway's phosphorus import needs by up to 40%.
          Collected sludge isn't just diverted waste — it's a domestic, renewable phosphorus
          source that doesn't yet exist at scale.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-brand-navy-950">From collection to a usable product</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-neutral-700">
          Collected sludge already has real uses — as fertilizer for conventional
          agriculture, as biogas feedstock, and increasingly as an input into the kind of
          circular bioeconomy that Nordic aquaculture is moving toward, where organic
          side-streams replace virgin, land- and freshwater-intensive feed ingredients.
          None of that is possible without collecting and concentrating the sludge in the
          first place — which is exactly where dissolved air flotation and mechanical
          dewatering do their work.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTA
    heading="Collection is the first step. We build the equipment for it."
    body="Explore our dissolved air flotation and sludge dewatering solutions, or talk to us about what's realistic for your site."
    ctaLabel={t('common.viewAllSolutions')}
    ctaHref={pathFor('solutions', lang)}
  />
</BaseLayout>
